Michele Remer

Bio

Michele is a PhD student at Michigan State University in the Fisheries and Wildlife department. She mainly researches Arctic tourism and its effects on invasive species in the Center for Systems Integration and Sustainability. Growing up in North Dakota near the Canadian border helped her to develop a very deep appreciation for colder climates and a love of snow, so she is interested in researching colder climates to protect these particularly vulnerable natural areas. In her free time, she enjoys reading, hiking, and biking and is currently attempting to add crocheting to her repertoire.

Education

Michigan State University | East Lansing, MI

PhD | May 2022 - August 2027

Saint Marys University of Minnesota | Winona, MN

B.A. in Environmental Biology, Zoology and Psychology Minors | September 2016 - May 2020

Experience

Strategic Conservation Solutions | Demmer Scholar Program Intern | May 2022 - August 2022

U.S. Army Corps of Engineers | Biological Science Technician | May 2021 - September 2021

American Conservation Experience | AmeriCorps Conservation Corps Member | August 2020 - April 2021

GeoSpatial Services | Geographic Information Systems Technician | May 2019 - August 2020

Saint Marys University of Minnesota | Environmental Science Intern | May 2018 - August 2018

Turtle River State Park | Seasonal Park Ranger | May 2017 - August 2017
